That's kind of the point of this talk, uh, is to, is, is to get there so

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:04.919
that you can tell them that you learned this one thing at a conference,

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:07.720
uh, apart from other things.

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:11.480
So welcome to the Jaffel shop.

00:01:11.519 --> 00:01:14.800
This is an example we use in dbt a lot.

00:01:14.879 --> 00:01:19.239
So a Jaffel is really just an Australian grilled cheese.

00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:21.000
And Australian grilled cheese.

00:01:21.839 --> 00:01:25.320
And essentially this is kind of our toy project.

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:29.080
And so you've been hired at this Jaffel shop in order to fix a

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:31.639
problem that sales have slowed a bit.

00:01:31.839 --> 00:01:34.919
So you kind of want to dig in and kind of reaccelerate that.

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:41.400
So the prompt you've gone from, uh, your boss is can we identify

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:44.519
high value customers with no recent orders?

00:01:44.559 --> 00:01:48.160
So we can email them a coupon, uh, because they may have just fallen

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:49.320
out of the habit of ordering.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:51.519
So they want to email them and get them back.

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:57.760
Um, and so if you notice like both of these phrases in italics, high value

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:03.519
customers, no recent orders are fairly vague, and so your job as a data

00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:08.320
engineer is often to kind of like, uh, turn these into metrics that

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:10.600
you can kind of go and identify.

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:14.039
So what do you have as raw ingredients?

00:02:14.039 --> 00:02:17.639
So you have these three CSV files, uh, maybe a bit small to read, but

00:02:17.639 --> 00:02:20.919
they're customers, orders, and payments, uh, that have come

00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:22.639
out of the different systems.

00:02:23.279 --> 00:02:28.160
Um, and you're also given kind of this ERD diagram between the different.

00:02:28.199 --> 00:02:33.440
And so you have order ID maps to like order ID, like order.ID maps to

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:39.479
payments.orderID, customers.ID maps to like, uh, orders.userID, so on and so forth.

00:02:39.639 --> 00:02:41.720
So you've been given these two things.

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:50.160
And what you decide to do is you decide to analyze, uh, analyze and kind of

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:54.279
break up the two different parts of the prompt into high value customers

00:02:54.279 --> 00:02:55.199
and no recent orders.

00:02:55.199 --> 00:02:58.759
So you decide to look at for high value customers, decide to look at number

00:02:58.759 --> 00:03:03.080
of orders and their lifetime value, which is the sum total of how much

00:03:03.080 --> 00:03:03.880
they've spent with you.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:08.639
And for no recent orders, you decide, okay, we'll look at the dates of their

00:03:08.639 --> 00:03:10.679
first order and their most recent order.

00:03:12.399 --> 00:03:15.520
So, uh, let's get cracking.

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:20.320
So essentially I'm going to speed through these next few slides because most of

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:24.240
you are probably very familiar with these, but this is kind of like data

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:24.839
extraction.

00:03:24.839 --> 00:03:30.639
So you read the CSVs in, uh, we prep the orders, we kind of group by customer

00:03:30.639 --> 00:03:35.000
ID and do some aggregates on like first order, most recent order, number of

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:35.520
orders.

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:42.559
Um, and then also on the payment, same, uh, group by customer ID, uh, and then

00:03:42.559 --> 00:03:45.279
convert from cents to dollars, right?

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:46.880
Very basic transformation.

00:03:47.839 --> 00:03:53.199
And so where this gets us is now we have, uh, the number of orders, the first

00:03:53.199 --> 00:03:57.600
order, most recent order, and we kind of need to get customer lifetime value.

00:03:58.360 --> 00:04:03.320
Um, and so what you do is essentially you take all of these, uh, data frames

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:07.479
that you had previously got, and you kind of assemble them, uh, and you do left

00:04:07.479 --> 00:04:12.320
joins from customers onto orders, payments, and then you like rename total

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:16.760
amount to LTV, and then you do select to get them in the right order.

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:20.760
This should be pretty standard for most of you.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:24.920
Uh, and now you have everything you need.

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:28.920
So what you decide to do is you decide to write this out.

00:04:29.079 --> 00:04:32.959
Uh, in my case, I'm writing it out to a CSV, but you could write it out

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:35.519
to a database or any other place.

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:39.959
Um, and then essentially you decide to visualize it, uh, in

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:41.720
this case on a shiny dashboard.

00:04:42.279 --> 00:04:47.040
Uh, so I think there's a natural break around $30 of lifetime value.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:50.359
So you decide to kind of take that as your break point.

00:04:50.799 --> 00:04:55.959
Um, and of course, like you can go play around with this a lot more, but be the

00:04:55.959 --> 00:05:02.040
long, uh, so what we've done is we've actually converted this vague prompt of

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:06.920
high value customers with no recent orders to customers with lifetime value

00:05:06.920 --> 00:05:12.519
greater than $30 and the most recent order more than 30 days ago, that second

00:05:12.519 --> 00:05:16.440
part is something you kind of like figure out this is a reasonable assumption to me.

00:05:16.559 --> 00:05:18.880
Um, cool.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:25.119
So, um, you do that and it's a hit, uh, the emails work on their

00:05:25.119 --> 00:05:27.480
customers who had forgotten that they love your product.

00:05:27.480 --> 00:05:32.079
So they come back and order more from you, uh, and all as well.

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:39.160
And so what we've actually stumbled on here is really the analytics

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:42.239
workflow, which is that you have raw data.

00:05:42.839 --> 00:05:44.720
That's kind of disorganized.

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:45.920
It may be a bit messy.

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:52.040
Uh, you, you have a transformation step, which is cleaning it, reorganizing it,

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:56.160
uh, testing and documenting, uh, these workflows and your data.

00:05:56.679 --> 00:06:01.519
And then a kind of final deployment step, uh, that produces these clean

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:07.239
data sets that you can then use, uh, downstream in your BI tools, your ML

00:06:07.239 --> 00:06:11.040
models, or any other kind of operational analytics you may want to do.

00:06:14.239 --> 00:06:20.000
And so the next thing that happens is you're about to go on holiday.

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:23.040
Uh, and your boss asks you, can you document and test this

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:24.959
workflow for the rest of the team?

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:27.880
And so you say, okay.

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:33.000
So the first thing you do is kind of like refactor it a bit.

00:06:33.119 --> 00:06:34.359
Uh, so it's a bit cleaner.

00:06:34.519 --> 00:06:39.559
Uh, this also hopefully you should be doing, uh, and then so

00:06:39.559 --> 00:06:41.519
you create this new is HB field.

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:43.959
And then you decide to document this.

00:06:43.959 --> 00:06:48.799
This is just mark down, uh, some notes, uh, which are what is customers?

00:06:48.839 --> 00:06:50.279
It's a dimensional model.

00:06:50.399 --> 00:06:54.839
Uh, so dimensional model is like, uh, data modeling terminology for

00:06:54.839 --> 00:06:57.480
saying like, this is an object.

00:06:57.480 --> 00:06:58.279
It's not a verb.

00:06:58.399 --> 00:07:03.679
Uh, it is a thing that doesn't really change, uh, of a customer.

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:07.679
Uh, how often it gets refreshed, which is daily, uh, and who maintains

00:07:07.679 --> 00:07:09.279
it like growth and pricing maintain.

00:07:09.839 --> 00:07:13.679
And then the different columns on it, which are like customer ID.

00:07:13.799 --> 00:07:17.399
Uh, and then of course, as you can see, we have to write some tests on it,

00:07:17.799 --> 00:07:21.320
which are that the customer ID should always be unique, uh,

00:07:21.359 --> 00:07:22.600
and it should never be null.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:26.839
Um, then a few other columns like first name, last name,

00:07:27.239 --> 00:07:28.920
first order, most recent order.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.720
Uh, this one, it's useful to document that these are UTC date times,

00:07:33.799 --> 00:07:35.480
um, because time zones are hard.

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:40.239
Uh, and we, we also want to add a constraint on most recent order that

00:07:40.239 --> 00:07:44.959
it should be greater than or equal to your first order number of orders.

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:48.160
Uh, customer LTV, like if you're not familiar with that term, you

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:49.359
should document what this is.

00:07:49.359 --> 00:07:51.679
Like sum of totals of all orders placed.

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:57.040
Uh, and this new flag we've introduced, which is, is high value is customer

00:07:57.040 --> 00:07:59.559
high LTV greater than or equal to 30.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:01.760
Okay.

00:08:02.119 --> 00:08:07.440
So I think one of the beautiful parts of documenting things this way is that

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:10.279
your tests just naturally flow out of your documentation.

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:13.480
It's not like you have to think of brand new tests to write.

00:08:13.720 --> 00:08:18.399
So from those documentation, we've got customer ID must be unique, not null.

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:22.760
High value is the lifetime value greater than or equal to 30, most recent

00:08:22.760 --> 00:08:28.959
order greater than or equal to first order, and then a new test, because we

00:08:28.959 --> 00:08:34.119
said that the, the data is refreshed daily, we've added in this new loaded

00:08:34.119 --> 00:08:39.239
at test that says that the data must be fresher than 36 hours in this case.

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:46.640
And then, so, so kind of going back to that diagram.

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:51.840
So there was a, there was document, there was test, and then now there's

00:08:51.840 --> 00:08:53.559
deploy is kind of like our last step.

00:08:54.039 --> 00:08:59.080
And there's a million different ways to deploy a data engineering workload.

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:01.840
So I'm not going to talk about any of them.

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:06.440
I'm just going to talk about a common pattern that you should maybe think

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:11.200
about when you do this, which is pretty useful, it's called write audit publish.

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:17.760
So the right is basically when you have new data, you write it

00:09:17.799 --> 00:09:20.520
to a separate place in staging.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:22.400
You don't write this to production.

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:29.760
When then you run tests on this new staging data to make sure that the

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:32.919
data quality is high it meets all the checks you would expect.

00:09:33.479 --> 00:09:36.159
And then finally you publish it to production.

00:09:36.719 --> 00:09:41.119
And so the goal of this is that there should never be

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:42.960
bad quality data in production.

00:09:43.239 --> 00:09:47.080
And the trade-off you're making here is that the data in production

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:49.679
might be slightly stale and that's okay.

00:09:50.479 --> 00:09:55.200
You'd rather kind of bias towards high quality data and then you can

00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:56.799
kind of go fix whatever is not.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:00.119
Cool.

00:10:00.159 --> 00:10:04.119
So we're kind of back at this part of the diagram, just the transformation

00:10:04.119 --> 00:10:08.000
block, which is we've developed this analysis, we've tested and

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:09.960
documented it and we've deployed it.

00:10:10.919 --> 00:10:16.679
So we've kind of gone through that whole life cycle and you're at happy

00:10:16.679 --> 00:10:21.559
hour when essentially somebody, one of your colleagues from another team

00:10:21.559 --> 00:10:24.719
comes up to you and says, Hey, we have something similar.

00:10:24.799 --> 00:10:28.200
We tag customers with more than three orders as prime.

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:30.280
You guys probably know where this is going.

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:38.119
And now you kind of have a problem in that you have two different definitions

00:10:38.119 --> 00:10:40.679
for what are essentially the same business metric.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:47.599
And so what you have to do now is do standardization, which is a really,

00:10:47.599 --> 00:10:50.039
really hard organizational challenge.

00:10:50.039 --> 00:10:51.679
It's not really a technical challenge.

00:10:51.679 --> 00:10:55.479
It's that you have to get two different teams to talk to each other, often

00:10:55.640 --> 00:11:00.679
two different VPs to kind of talk to each other, agree on a definition, do

00:11:00.679 --> 00:11:05.119
the analysis for how metrics might change, how to communicate that change

00:11:05.119 --> 00:11:06.760
to all your different stakeholders.

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:15.479
This is hard work, but it is so very worth it to do it just so that when another

00:11:15.479 --> 00:11:21.400
team member from another team kind of talks about a metric, you know exactly

00:11:21.799 --> 00:11:25.000
what they're saying and what the caveats of that metric are going

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.880
to be and everything else.

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:33.359
And so this is an important part of a data engineer's job that often isn't

00:11:33.359 --> 00:11:38.559
really captured, but it, and it's not captured, it's also like not technical.

00:11:38.640 --> 00:11:41.440
It's not a technical part of your job, but I think it is an important

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:43.440
part of a data engineer's job.

00:11:44.719 --> 00:11:45.039
Cool.

00:11:45.239 --> 00:11:49.520
So this is, I had to put this slide in because these things often take a lot

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:56.799
of time, one eternity later, you decide on a standardized definition, which is

00:11:56.799 --> 00:11:58.520
that you decide to do both, right?

00:11:58.760 --> 00:12:03.760
You decide that the lifetime value is greater than or equal to 30 and your

00:12:03.760 --> 00:12:06.479
number of orders are greater than three.

00:12:07.119 --> 00:12:11.919
So this is kind of like you've redefined this is high value flag to

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:13.679
include both of these definitions.

00:12:13.719 --> 00:12:14.880
It doesn't always go this way.

00:12:14.880 --> 00:12:18.719
Sometimes it kind of can differ, but this is kind of what you've

00:12:18.719 --> 00:12:26.119
landed on and so what we've actually stumbled on here is we've worked

00:12:26.159 --> 00:12:31.239
backwards into this definition that I like of data models, which is that.

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:35.840
It is a structured representation in our case, a CSV file.

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:38.440
In your case, this might be a database table.

00:12:38.479 --> 00:12:43.760
It could be any other format that you put your data in that organizes.

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:47.960
So we've combined data from different sources, from your raw customer

00:12:47.960 --> 00:12:53.239
data, your raw payments data, your raw transactions data, and we've

00:12:53.239 --> 00:12:57.880
standardized the data across these two different teams who had two different

00:12:57.880 --> 00:13:04.200
definitions of what high value customer is to enable and guide human and machine

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:09.080
behavior, inform decision-making and facilitate actions and I think that last

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:12.280
part is like the most important part of this definition.

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:17.919
The reason we all do data work is so that we can facilitate some

00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:19.919
actions within our organizations.

00:13:21.320 --> 00:13:25.640
And I think it's like really important to keep that in our sites when we

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:27.400
kind of like build this data model.

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:29.159
What are we building it for?

00:13:31.400 --> 00:13:31.919
Cool.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:39.559
So hopefully I've had you convinced, but if not, this is why model data, which

00:13:40.559 --> 00:13:43.280
is why do it in the first place?

00:13:43.479 --> 00:13:49.760
All this talk, fine and dandy, but what are the practical benefits of it?

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:50.159
Right.

00:13:51.479 --> 00:13:57.080
And I think for me, it all just boils down to that helps you scale, right?

00:13:57.520 --> 00:14:03.520
And so this is kind of a pretty picture of a DAG, which is a directed acyclic

00:14:03.679 --> 00:14:09.640
graph of all your transformations, which is, and so each node, you can kind of

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:13.599
think of it as one of the transformations you've done.

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:22.119
And even at this scale, it is kind of tricky to get it to work reliably if you

00:14:22.119 --> 00:14:26.039
don't do all of the things we've kind of been talking about thus far, which is

00:14:26.039 --> 00:14:30.919
like documenting your code, testing your code, using write, audit, publish.

00:14:31.919 --> 00:14:37.719
And so it's hard at this scale, but it's almost impossible at this scale, right?

00:14:37.719 --> 00:14:43.640
Which is kind of like my company's internal data transformation framework.

00:14:43.640 --> 00:14:45.880
Like there's just too many lines going everywhere.

00:14:45.880 --> 00:14:46.960
There's too many nodes.

00:14:47.719 --> 00:14:49.520
You cannot even read what's on the screen.

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:55.280
But it's kind of impossible to kind of go in, figure out what's going

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:58.840
wrong, fix it in timely fashion.

00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:04.679
So this is where this tool of data modeling kind of really helps

00:15:04.679 --> 00:15:06.960
you scale and operate at this level.

00:15:08.520 --> 00:15:09.479
So cool.

00:15:09.840 --> 00:15:11.559
How do you get started, right?

00:15:13.719 --> 00:15:19.119
So I think the most important thing to take is that data modeling is a process.

00:15:19.159 --> 00:15:20.719
There's no end state.

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:25.200
It is something that you keep doing within your organization.

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:28.280
So I guess the tips I have is start small.

00:15:28.479 --> 00:15:35.760
You don't have to like start all the way from, you don't, you don't have to start

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:40.080
all the way by taking like two weeks off your sprint and just documenting everything.

00:15:40.119 --> 00:15:41.080
That doesn't really work.

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:46.760
So maybe if there's something that's confusing to newcomers, start documenting that.

00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:52.440
If there's a dataset or a metric that's not super intuitive, start documenting that.

00:15:53.159 --> 00:15:56.880
Keep iterating, like different teams and different organizations will have

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:58.479
different things that work for them.

00:15:58.840 --> 00:16:01.960
So just kind of like figure out what works for you.

00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:07.200
And lastly, because it's a process, you should have fun with it.

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:13.640
And you, and there's, there's nothing better than kind of going off on holiday

00:16:14.520 --> 00:16:19.840
and then having, having your team change something and then you come back and you

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:24.400
immediately know what, what changed because the documentation was there, the tests

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:27.679
were there, they're standardized, all of that stuff.

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:34.039
And so the toolkit is kind of stuff we've talked about already, but these are kind

00:16:34.039 --> 00:16:37.719
of like the three things you can start doing, which is documentation, testing,

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:42.159
standardization, standardization I've put as a present because it is a

00:16:42.159 --> 00:16:43.520
present to your organization.

00:16:47.599 --> 00:16:53.119
And I think kind of the last thing I'll say is that it is a tool agnostic practice.

00:16:53.719 --> 00:16:55.840
Like you can do data modeling in Excel.

00:16:55.880 --> 00:16:58.599
I'm sure none of you will do it here, but you could.

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:01.760
It's kind of the point, you can do it in any tool.

00:17:02.679 --> 00:17:07.719
The company I work at, dbt labs kind of makes a tool for data modeling with all

00:17:07.719 --> 00:17:11.239
of these practices built in, in a natural way.

00:17:12.479 --> 00:17:18.079
And so that's kind of an easy way to get started.

00:17:18.079 --> 00:17:22.719
You could write Python or SQL in dbt and it works on a bunch of different data

00:17:22.719 --> 00:17:23.359
warehouses.

00:17:24.719 --> 00:17:29.439
And so congrats, you're now equipped to model data from new sources.

00:17:29.479 --> 00:17:35.920
Like if you bring in a new payment source or stuff like that, you now have the

00:17:35.920 --> 00:17:38.479
tools to do it with compound metrics.

00:17:38.479 --> 00:17:43.599
So like if you want to find out a ratio of like customer acquisition costs to

00:17:43.599 --> 00:17:45.439
lifetime value, stuff like that.

00:17:45.719 --> 00:17:51.319
And of course with changing definitions, because every organization, like even if

00:17:51.319 --> 00:17:54.920
your code is right, like your organization will change over time.

00:17:55.319 --> 00:17:58.479
And so your definitions and your data needs to change with it.

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:03.719
And lastly, if you want to explore further, I think this is a good textbook on the

00:18:03.719 --> 00:18:07.640
topic, Fundamentals of Data Engineering by Joe Rees and Matt Housley.

00:18:08.439 --> 00:18:10.479
And that's all I had.

00:18:10.599 --> 00:18:11.000
Thank you.

